{{nihongo|'''''Kujiki'''''|旧事紀|}}, or {{nihongo|'''''Sendai Kuji Hongi'''''|先代旧事本紀|}}, is a historical Japanese text. It was generally believed to have been one of the earliest Japanese histories until the middle of the [[Edo period]], when scholars such as [[Tokugawa Mitsukuni]] successfully contended that it was an imitation based on the ''[[Nihon shoki]]'', the ''[[Kojiki]]'', and the ''[[Kogo shūi]]''.<ref>[http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=1250 Critics by Japanese scholars]</ref> In 2006 this opinion was challenged by [[John R. Bentley]], who, based on his examinations of extant manuscripts, made a sophisticated argument for ''Kujiki'' having been written during the early eighth century. It is too soon to say whether Bentley's argument will be accepted by scholars.
