{{Shintoism}}
{{more footnotes|date=November 2011}}
{{nihongo|'''''Kujiki'''''|旧事紀|}}, or {{nihongo|'''''Sendai Kuji Hongi'''''|先代旧事本紀|}}, is a historical Japanese text. It was generally believed to have been one of the earliest Japanese histories until the middle of the [[Edo period]], when scholars such as [[Tokugawa Mitsukuni]] successfully contended that it was an imitation based on the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'', the ''[[Kojiki]]'' and the ''[[Kogo Shūi]]''.<ref>[http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=1250 Critics by Japanese scholars]</ref> In 2006, this opinion was challenged by [[John R. Bentley]], who argued based on his examinations of extant manuscripts that the ''Kujiki'' was indeed written in the early eighth century CE, before the the ''[[Kogo Shūi]]'', and as part of the same historiographical movement that produced the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'' and the ''[[Kojiki]]''. Bentley's argument is not yet much discussed in the scholarly literature.
Ten volumes in length, it covers the history of ancient Japan through [[Empress Suiko]], third daughter of [[Emperor Kimmei]]. The preface is supposedly written by [[Soga no Umako]] (+626). While it includes many quotes from ''[[Kojiki]]'' (712) and ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'' (720), volumes five and ten contain unique materials. The overall composition is considered as having been compiled between 807 and 936.
